SYMPTOM

New employee is unable to access the department's shared drive. The drive is not mapped on their computer, and attempting to access the provided network path returns a "Network path not found" error.

ISOLATION

Troubleshooting performed:

Confirmed the user started in the department last week.
Verified the shared drive is not mapped on the user's computer.
Confirmed coworkers can access the shared drive without issues.
Verified the user is connected to the office's wired network.
Determined the issue is isolated to the user's account or workstation.
ROOT CAUSE

The user had not been granted access to the department's shared drive, or the network drive had not been mapped during the onboarding process.

FIX
Checked the file server documentation to identify the correct shared folder and required security group.
Verified the user's Active Directory group memberships.
Added the user to the appropriate security group (or requested the required access if approval was needed).
Mapped the department shared drive using the correct network path.
Asked the user to sign out and back in (or refreshed Group Policy) so the new permissions would apply.
VERIFICATION

User successfully accessed the department's shared drive, opened the required folders and files, and confirmed they could perform their work.

PREVENTION
Include shared drive permissions and drive mapping in the new employee onboarding checklist.
Automate drive mapping through Group Policy where possible.
Verify department access before the employee's first working day.
